# Project Security Best Practices

## Domain Layer Security

### Domain Entities Protection
- Keep entities simple with public readonly fields for IDs
- Use enums for controlled values (status, roles)
- Avoid complex business logic in entities
- Use proper typing for all entity fields
- Keep entities focused on data structure only

```typescript
// Good: Simple domain entity (src/domain/entities)
import { RoleEnum } from './role.entity'

export class UserEntity {
  public readonly id!: number
  public username!: string
  password!: string // Will be hashed by infrastructure
  public role!: RoleEnum
  public lastLogin?: Date
  public readonly createdAt!: Date
  public readonly updatedAt!: Date
}
```

### Domain Services Security
- Keep sensitive business logic in domain services (src/domain/services)
- Implement domain events for audit trails
- Use domain exceptions for business rule violations (src/domain/exceptions)
- Never let infrastructure concerns leak into domain layer

### Repository Interfaces Security
- Define clear contracts for data access in domain layer (src/domain/repositories)
- Include security requirements in repository interfaces
- Use domain-specific types and entities
- Define proper method signatures with security in mind
- Never include implementation details

```typescript
// Good: Secure repository interface (src/domain/repositories)
export const USER_REPOSITORY = 'USER_REPOSITORY_INTERFACE'
export interface IUserRepository {
  getUserByUsername(username: string): Promise<UserEntity | null>
  getUserById(id: number): Promise<UserEntity | null>
  updateLastLogin(id: number): Promise<void>
  // No direct password access methods - handled through auth services
}
```

### Service Interfaces Security
- Define security service contracts in domain layer (src/domain/services)
- Never expose sensitive implementation details
- Use proper typing for security operations
- Define clear contracts for authentication and authorization

```typescript
// Good: Secure service interfaces (src/domain/services)
export const BCRYPT_SERVICE = 'BCRYPT_SERVICE_INTERFACE'
export interface IBcryptService {
  hash(hashString: string): Promise<string>
  compare(password: string, hashPassword: string): Promise<boolean>
  // Simple contract, no salt exposure or implementation details
}
```

### Configuration Interfaces Security
- Define configuration contracts in domain layer (src/domain/config)
- Never include default values or sensitive information
- Use proper typing for configuration parameters
- Keep interfaces focused and minimal

```typescript
// Good: Secure configuration interfaces (src/domain/config)
export interface IDatabaseConfig {
  getDatabaseEngine(): string
  getDatabaseHost(): string
  getDatabasePort(): number
  getDatabaseUser(): string
  getDatabasePassword(): string
  getDatabaseName(): string
  getDatabaseSchema(): string
  getDatabaseSync(): boolean
  // Only method signatures, no implementations or defaults
}

export interface IJwtConfig {
  getJwtSecret(): string
  getJwtExpirationTime(): string
  getJwtRefreshSecret(): string
